Titanic Analysis¶

Introduction¶

The RMS Titanic was a British passenger liner that gained global fame due to its tragic sinking on its maiden voyage in April 1912. At the time, the Titanic was one of the largest and most luxurious ships ever built, often referred to as the "unsinkable" ship. The disaster occurred during the night of April 14-15, 1912, when the ship struck an iceberg in the North Atlantic Ocean.¶
The Titanic was part of the White Star Line's trio of Olympic-class ocean liners, which also included the RMS Olympic and HMHS Britannic. It was constructed in the Harland and Wolff shipyards in Belfast, Northern Ireland. The ship was heralded for its opulence and cutting-edge technology.¶
The Titanic set sail on its maiden voyage from Southampton, England, on April 10, 1912, with stops in Cherbourg, France, and Queenstown (now known as Cobh), Ireland, before heading across the Atlantic to its final destination, New York City. On the night of April 14, 1912, the Titanic struck an iceberg about 375 miles south of Newfoundland. The iceberg caused significant damage to the ship's hull, leading to its eventual sinking. The ship carried a limited number of lifeboats, and the evacuation process was chaotic, resulting in the loss of over 1500 lives.¶
The Titanic carried a diverse group of passengers, including wealthy industrialists, immigrants seeking a new life in America, and crew members. The class distinction among passengers became notable during the evacuation, as first-class passengers were given priority access to lifeboats.¶
The sinking of the Titanic captured global attention and shocked the world. The media extensively covered the disaster, and the public was deeply affected by the loss of life. The tragedy led to changes in maritime safety regulations and practices.¶
The sinking of the Titanic has become a symbol of human hubris and the unpredictable forces of nature. Numerous books, documentaries, and films have been produced about the Titanic, contributing to its enduring place in popular culture.¶

Objective:¶

The primary objective of this project is to conduct a comprehensive analysis of the Titanic dataset, shedding light on patterns, correlations, and insights that can deepen our understanding of the events surrounding the disaster. I seek to answer a multitude of questions, exploring the impact of socio-economic factors, family relationships, age, gender, and other variables on the likelihood of survival. Through statistical analysis and visualization techniques, I aim to discern underlying trends, draw meaningful conclusions, and contribute to the broader narrative of the Titanic tragedy.¶

Conclusion¶

The overall survival rate on the Titanic was approximately 38.38%.¶
Passengers in certain classes (Pclass) had varying chances of survival, but the passengers under "1" have higher survival rate.¶
Gender also played a significant role in survival rates, with females having a considerably higher survival rate compared to males.¶
The findings did also showed that factors such as class, gender, and family relationships were crucial in determining survival outcomes.¶
The age distribution of passengers revealed that the Oldest passenger was close to 100 years.¶
Children, particularly those under 18, were given priority in lifeboats, resulting in a higher survival rate for this age group.¶
Passengers who paid more for their tickets had a higher chance of survival.¶
There was a positive correlation between ticket fare and passenger class, suggesting that fare and class were related.¶
The number of passengers who embarked from Southampton, Cherbourg, and Queenstown were 644, 168 and 77 respectively.¶
The average family size on the Titanic was 0.90.¶
Passengers traveling alone had a different survival rate compared to those with family members aboard, indicating that family size influenced survival.¶
A limited number of passengers had cabin information available.¶
The color indicates whether the data is missing (yellow) or present (purple).¶
This analysis of the Titanic dataset has provided valuable insights into the factors that influenced the survival of passengers. It highlights the significance of passenger class, gender, age, family size, and other factors in determining survival outcomes during one of the most infamous maritime disasters in history.¶
This project serves as a testament to the importance of data analysis in unraveling historical events and uncovering patterns that can inform our understanding of human behavior in times of crisis.¶
